    +sub-title( "Usage example" )

    :marked
        Because Eezo should have a pretty flat specificity
        tree, it should always be possible to override the
        weight of an element by applying the `.fw-*` class
        to it.

    :prismjs( language = "html" )
        <h1 class="fs-i"> heading is italic <h1>

        <em> text is italic </em>
        <em class="fs-n"> text is normal </em>
        <em class="fs-n fw-b"> text is oblique(ish) </em>

    +sub-title( "Media Queries" )

    :marked
        No media query support; `font-style` should be *meaningful*,
        and the same for all viewers regardless of their medium.

    +sub-title( "Customising" )

    +small-title( "Default Classes" )

    :marked
        It's possible you don't like the prefix `fs-` and want
        something else, or nothing... you can modify the `$font-style-prop`
        variable to achieve this.

    :prismjs( language = "scss" )
        // change the default class:
        // .fs-*  ->  ""
        $font-style-prop: "";

    +small-title( "Custom Styles" )

    :marked
        Also the `$font-styles` map can be overridden,
        although I don't see any need for it.

    :prismjs( language = "scss" )
        // change the styles so we can use oblique.
        $font-styles: (
          normal:   normal,
          italic:   italic,
          oblique:  oblique
        );

    +small-title( "Combined" )

    :marked
        The previous two customisations combined:

    :prismjs( language = "scss" )
        // would result in css like:
        .normal   { font-style: normal; }
        .italic   { font-style: italic; }
        .oblique  { font-style: oblique; }

